    <title>Combined summary - [Mempool spam] Should we as developers reject non-standard Taproot transactions from full nodes?</title>
    <updated>2023-06-16T18:22:32.691949+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2023-May/021620.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin-dev mailing list has been discussing the recent congestion in the Bitcoin mempool caused by high volume side projects such as BRC-20, which is pricing out real Bitcoin transactions. Ali Sherief suggests curbing the unintended consequences of BIP 342 by introducing a consensus rule change, enforcing censorship at the node level to prune non-standard Taproot transactions, or introducing a run-time option to instantly prune all non-standard Taproot transactions. However, Michael Folkson argues that rejecting any transaction where the fee is higher than the sum of the outputs would impinge on a valid use case and require a consensus rule change. Erik Aronesty proposes an easier solution to reject such transactions. The discussion also explores the purpose of paying an on-chain transaction fee greater than the amount received and possible benefits of facilitating dust transactions.Luke Dashjr criticized the lack of action taken to filter out spam transactions in Bitcoin Core and suggested using OP_RETURN or other data embedding schemes to handle spam transactions. Additionally, the lack of Lightning wallets for desktop is an issue in the ecosystem, and more GUI wallets are needed. The impact of non-monetary use on network stability and game theory was also discussed. Erik Aronesty argued that storing real estate ownership or NFTs on the Bitcoin network is dangerous to network stability, as it throws off the incentive logic for mining fees. He suggested creating a permanent incentive to keep this kind of stuff off Bitcoin by going at the "incentive/economic layer." Meanwhile, Michael Folkson argued against rejecting any transaction where the fee is higher than the sum of the outputs, as it would prevent valid use cases like closing a Lightning channel during a protracted fee spike.The community discusses possible solutions to the problem of congestion caused by side projects like BRC-20, including enforcing censorship at the node level and introducing a runtime option to prune non-standard Taproot transactions or BIPs and commits into the Bitcoin Core codebase. Critics argue that such actions impinge on maximum freedom, but the community has a responsibility to find a solution that fits everyone's common ground. Finally, there are two possible options for allocating space in the block for non-standard transactions. The first is to allocate only up to 10% of the space in the block for non-standard transactions, while the second is to change the architecture in such a way that onchain ordinals transactions become much more expensive, forcing them onto their own type of Lightning Network.There has been significant congestion in the Bitcoin mempool, caused by high volume side projects such as BRC-20. This threatens the smooth and normal use of the Bitcoin network as a peer-to-peer digital currency. To address this issue, Ali Sherief proposed two potential solutions: (i) BIPs and/or (ii) commits into the Bitcoin Core codebase, to curtail the loophole in BIP 342 which defines the validation rules for Taproot scripts, or (iii) enforce censorship at the node level and introduce a run-time option to instantly prune all non-standard Taproot transactions. However, there may be criticisms about these potential solutions, so it is important to find a common ground solution.Keagan McClelland expresses concerns over the current fee environment for Bitcoin and its survival in the post-subsidy era. They suggest maintaining the Store-of-Value feature of Bitcoin while reducing network difficulty and compromising security and intervening where there is no free market. Ali Sherief acknowledges that some people may criticize the proposed solutions, but emphasizes the need to find a common ground solution. Weiji proposes a new opcode called OP_ZKP to enable payments based on zero-knowledge proof and address transaction fee issues.Overall, the discussion highlights the challenges of balancing the needs of different stakeholders and finding solutions that maintain the smooth operation of the Bitcoin network while accommodating new projects and technologies. There are concerns over the recent congestion in the Bitcoin mempool caused by high volume side projects like BRC-20. This is pricing out real bitcoin transactions and disrupting the harmony of the network. Despite criticisms from absolutists/libertarians/maximum-freedom advocates, a solution needs to be found to prevent congestion caused by side projects such as BRC-20. One option is to introduce a run-time option to instantly prune all non-standard Taproot transactions. Ultimately, the Bitcoin network needs a solution for long-term horrible fees problem that fits everyone's common ground. It is important to find solutions that balance the needs of different stakeholders, including developers, miners, and users.</summary>
